In code 1, the constructor for `Parent` has no arguments, so a call to the default one is implicit:

    public Child () {
        super();
    } /* This code is not necessary, but is implied. */

But in codes 2 and 3, the constructor has a parameter, and since there is no overload provided with no parameters, then a call to the superclass constructor _must_ be provided. To do this, you must reference `super()`.

    public class Parent {
        public int a;

        public Parent(int number) {
            this.a = number;
        }
    }

    public class Child extends Parent {
        public Child(int numb) {
            super(numb); // Calls Parent(int) and sets this instance’s Parent.a value to numb.
        }
    }

